# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __enter__, __exit__, __call__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __enter__: false for all 10 — sync context manager protocol not in own __dict__.
# __exit__:  false for all 10 — sync context manager protocol not in own __dict__.
# __call__:  false for all 10 — callable protocol not in own __dict__.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their context
#   manager support uses the async protocol (__aenter__/__aexit__), not the
#   synchronous protocol (__enter__/__exit__). The callable protocol is not
#   part of the asyncio type API surface.
# asyncio.Lock/Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore/Condition note: these types DO support
#   'async with' via __aenter__/__aexit__ defined in their own __dict__. However,
#   the synchronous __enter__/__exit__ protocol is NOT defined in their own __dict__.
#   This wave confirms that __enter__ and __exit__ are each false for all 10 types.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue note: these queue types expose their API
#   via get()/put() coroutines and qsize()/empty()/full() methods. No context
#   manager or callable protocol dunders are defined in their own __dict__.
# asyncio.Task/Future note: these types represent in-progress coroutine execution
#   and results. They are not context managers and not callable. All three dunders
#   are absent from their own __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

